WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.420
[Amit Varma]: Among the few things I have learnt in my life, one is this, be selective about the things

00:00:11.420 --> 00:00:17.340
[Amit Varma]: you get involved in. I am still some way off from mastering the fine art of being dispassionate,

00:00:17.340 --> 00:00:21.680
[Amit Varma]: but more and more, when I watch the outrage erupt on social media, or the newest scandal

00:00:21.680 --> 00:00:26.900
[Amit Varma]: on news television, I tell myself not to get involved, not to get all het up about it.

00:00:26.900 --> 00:00:33.480
[Amit Varma]: My slogan to live by is a simple one, not my circus, not my monkeys. My power to change

00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:38.760
[Amit Varma]: the world is limited, so why sweat what I cannot control. Now I would imagine that this

00:00:38.760 --> 00:00:44.100
[Amit Varma]: is what many economists would think if they were actually asked to become a part of government

00:00:44.100 --> 00:00:50.200
[Amit Varma]: and help run the economy, especially in India, known for its oppressive state, so resistant

00:00:50.200 --> 00:00:56.080
[Amit Varma]: to change, and its venal toxic politics. Why get involved? Stay away and pontificate from

00:00:56.080 --> 00:01:01.480
[Amit Varma]: a mile-high view. My guest on the show today is a well-known economist who was asked six

00:01:01.480 --> 00:01:07.280
[Amit Varma]: years ago to join our central government as the chief economic advisor. He might well

00:01:07.280 --> 00:01:13.640
[Amit Varma]: have refused the offer, thinking, not my circus, not my monkeys. But he did not. He joined

00:01:13.640 --> 00:01:14.640
[Amit Varma]: the circus.

00:01:14.640 --> 00:01:23.840
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioural

00:01:23.840 --> 00:01:28.000
[Unknown]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:35.080
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen. My title for this episode is, What a Long Strange Trip

00:01:35.080 --> 00:01:39.480
[Amit Varma]: It's Been. And I'm actually referring to two trips here. One is that of the Indian economy

00:01:39.480 --> 00:01:44.720
[Amit Varma]: through 70 years, a complex monster passing through complicated times, starting small

00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:50.240
[Amit Varma]: and ending troubled. The second journey is that of my guest Arvind Subramanian, who joined

00:01:50.240 --> 00:01:56.400
[Amit Varma]: Arindra Modi's government in 2014 as chief economic advisor, excited about having the

00:01:56.400 --> 00:02:00.840
[Amit Varma]: chance to do work that could have an impact on the lives of millions. He held that post

00:02:00.840 --> 00:02:06.120
[Amit Varma]: for four years and continues to speak out today as a public intellectual. I was delighted

00:02:06.120 --> 00:02:10.560
[Amit Varma]: when he agreed to come on the show to speak about both India's journey in the last 73

00:02:10.560 --> 00:02:15.840
[Amit Varma]: years and his own in the four years he spent in government. I have been a constant critic

00:02:15.840 --> 00:02:20.760
[Amit Varma]: of this government's economic policies and did not refrain from asking hard questions.

00:02:20.760 --> 00:02:25.960
[Amit Varma]: Arvind, showing tremendous grace and patience, gave me forthright answers for more than three

00:02:25.960 --> 00:02:31.000
[Amit Varma]: hours. I'm sure even his former boss, Arun Jaitley, never grilled him for so long. No,

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:36.400
[Amit Varma]: but seriously, this was one of those digressive conversations that I really enjoyed spending

00:02:36.400 --> 00:02:41.400
[Amit Varma]: as much time on large meta questions as on policy nitty-gritties. Do note one thing,

00:02:41.400 --> 00:02:46.600
[Amit Varma]: by the way, due to a technical glitch, there was some minor sound disturbances in the recording,

00:02:46.600 --> 00:02:50.800
[Amit Varma]: which we have tried to cover up in the edit. I'm sure you'll get lost in the engrossing

00:02:50.800 --> 00:02:55.860
[Amit Varma]: flow of ideas and not even notice. Before we begin our conversation, though, let's take

00:02:55.860 --> 00:03:05.240
[Amit Varma]: a quick commercial break. Are you one of those people who not only loves to read, but also

00:03:05.240 --> 00:03:09.840
[Amit Varma]: wants to write better? If so, I have something for you. Since April this year, I've been

00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:14.880
[Amit Varma]: teaching an online course called The Art of Clear Writing. Four webinars spread out over

00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:19.240
[Amit Varma]: four Saturdays, in which I share whatever I've learnt about the craft and practice of

00:03:19.240 --> 00:03:25.480
[Amit Varma]: writing over 25 years as a professional writer. The course also contains many writing exercises,

00:03:25.480 --> 00:03:31.840
[Amit Varma]: discussions on email and WhatsApp, and much interactivity. It costs rupees 10,000 or $150.

00:03:31.840 --> 00:03:37.160
[Amit Varma]: You can check out the details at IndiaUncut.com slash clear writing. This link will be in

00:03:37.160 --> 00:03:40.560
[Amit Varma]: the show notes. If you want to bridge the gap between the thoughts in your head and

00:03:40.560 --> 00:03:46.520
[Amit Varma]: the words on the page, then the art of clear writing might be just what you need. September

00:03:46.520 --> 00:03:52.360
[Amit Varma]: batches begin on Saturday, September 5th. So hurry and register before then. IndiaUncut.com

00:03:52.360 --> 00:04:01.480
[Amit Varma]: slash clear writing. Arvind, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:04:01.480 --> 00:04:05.680
[Amit Varma]: Thanks, Amit. It's great to be on the show. You know, before we start talking about your

00:04:05.680 --> 00:04:09.480
[Amit Varma]: exciting career and various aspects of that are so interesting to me, both your time as

00:04:09.480 --> 00:04:13.800
[Amit Varma]: an economist and your time working as you know, in the government to actually bring

00:04:13.800 --> 00:04:19.080
[Amit Varma]: about change. I want to talk a little bit about your sort of personal growth, because

00:04:19.080 --> 00:04:23.320
[Amit Varma]: I was sort of looking at your CV. And I found it very interesting in the sense that I assumed

00:04:23.320 --> 00:04:27.560
[Amit Varma]: that, oh, you know, you must have taken the typical economist path where you've kind of

00:04:27.560 --> 00:04:32.400
[Amit Varma]: gone abroad and done a PhD and all of that. But you actually, you know, you did an MBA

00:04:32.400 --> 00:04:38.000
[Amit Varma]: from IIM Ahmedabad. And what I can see from all your public readings and speeches is that

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:43.520
[Amit Varma]: unlike the, you know, most economists have this almost as dry reputation and of not being

00:04:43.520 --> 00:04:47.840
[Amit Varma]: interested in other things and always, you know, engrossed in numbers, but you actually

00:04:47.840 --> 00:04:53.000
[Amit Varma]: given a lecture on, you know, the what economists can learn from literature, you are the only

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:58.680
[Amit Varma]: person I can think of who can quote both Keats and Keynes. So tell me a little bit about

00:04:58.680 --> 00:05:03.600
[Amit Varma]: your time growing up your formative influences and you know, what your personal journey was

00:05:03.600 --> 00:05:04.600
[Guest]: like.

00:05:04.600 --> 00:05:11.440
[Guest]: Right. You know, it's a bit always a little bit awkward to talk about oneself, of course.

00:05:11.440 --> 00:05:17.480
[Guest]: But I mean, let me just begin by saying that, when I said it's great to be on the podcast,

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:23.640
[Guest]: I should have added that it's almost now a mark of you only arrive as a public intellectual

00:05:23.640 --> 00:05:30.560
[Guest]: in India, when you've been on Amit Verma's podcast, I think this is a certification.

00:05:30.560 --> 00:05:36.160
[Guest]: So thanks for having me on the show. Yes. So in terms of, you know, growing up in a

00:05:36.160 --> 00:05:43.600
[Guest]: very kind of pretty conventional middle, upper middle class household, my father was in the

00:05:43.600 --> 00:05:50.320
[Guest]: government, he was in the Audit and Account Service. And he was a very unusual civil servant,

00:05:50.320 --> 00:05:56.600
[Guest]: you know, he was posted in the most godforsaken places, where everyone would try and want

00:05:56.600 --> 00:06:01.440
[Guest]: to be in Delhi, whatever he would, you know, we spent five years in Dandekarania, you know,

00:06:01.440 --> 00:06:07.960
[Guest]: in Nagaland, Shillong, you know, Ajmer, Udaipur, so I've, you know, traveled all over with

00:06:07.960 --> 00:06:14.840
[Guest]: him. And then I, you know, and of course, he was also a painter and a writer. And and

00:06:14.840 --> 00:06:20.360
[Guest]: so, so so the growing up the household was full of books and things. And, and what I

00:06:20.360 --> 00:06:24.480
[Guest]: remember, of course, is that, even when I was growing up, you know, this was what in

00:06:24.480 --> 00:06:31.560
[Guest]: the 60s, my father used to subscribe to, you know, Time, Newsweek, Life, all these things

00:06:31.560 --> 00:06:35.840
[Guest]: would physically come to the household. So, you know, just almost by osmosis, not that,

00:06:35.840 --> 00:06:40.600
[Guest]: you know, I was particularly studious or anything, but just by osmosis, you know, I could pick

00:06:40.600 --> 00:06:47.400
[Guest]: it up. And, you know, I have to say that, so just to give a give an example of, you

00:06:47.400 --> 00:06:52.680
[Guest]: know, things that we pick up that we forget that we've picked up unconsciously. So one

00:06:52.680 --> 00:06:59.440
[Guest]: of my, you know, all time favorite pieces on foreign aid, which I teach in class, is

00:06:59.440 --> 00:07:06.640
[Guest]: by this New Yorker writer called Philip Gurevich. He also has a great book on Rwanda on the

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:12.800
[Guest]: Rwanda genocide. And, you know, in the early part of the book, he describes the first foreign

00:07:12.800 --> 00:07:16.680
[Guest]: aid intervention, which is on one of the early foreign aid interventions, which was, you

00:07:16.680 --> 00:07:22.200
[Guest]: know, what happened in Nigeria and Biafra. And he has a line describing, you know, the

00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:27.080
[Guest]: famine that happened. And he describes, you know, children with, you know, the victims

00:07:27.080 --> 00:07:35.280
[Guest]: of the famine as stick limbed, balloon bellied, ancient eyed. And, you know, I was just blown

00:07:35.280 --> 00:07:41.000
[Guest]: by that description. But then I remember that the reason why it, you know, it evoked so

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:46.880
[Guest]: much in me was because I remember these pictures in Life magazine of the Biafra crisis and

00:07:46.880 --> 00:07:51.920
[Guest]: that picture of the of the boy or the child, actually, with the distended belly and so

00:07:51.920 --> 00:07:58.240
[Guest]: on. So I mean, this is just an aside growing up. So then I finished my at about the age

00:07:58.240 --> 00:08:04.720
[Guest]: of 13. You know, my elder brother was was a voracious reader, but I was not. But at

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:10.160
[Guest]: the age of 13 or 14, suddenly I realized that, you know, wow, that's this whole world of

00:08:10.160 --> 00:08:18.800
[Guest]: books out there, which I've not at all explored. So almost as a conscious act of catching up

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:23.520
[Guest]: on lost time, I would ask my brother to give me a list of, you know, 10, 15 books every

00:08:23.520 --> 00:08:27.720
[Guest]: time he would come. He was in college and I was still in school. So, you know, I started

00:08:27.720 --> 00:08:31.920
[Guest]: reading quite voraciously then. And then, of course, you know, finished my schooling

00:08:31.920 --> 00:08:39.040
[Guest]: from Chennai and went to Delhi to do an undergraduate degree in economics. I think it was fairly

00:08:39.040 --> 00:08:43.680
[Guest]: unremarkable. I think I think what was great about that period was we picked up almost

00:08:43.680 --> 00:08:48.960
[Guest]: everything from our peers. So it was really a great, you know, my love of Hindustani music,

00:08:48.960 --> 00:08:53.520
[Guest]: you know, a love of, you know, sports literature, reading and all of that was intensified in

00:08:53.520 --> 00:08:57.680
[Guest]: now. Of course, growing up, you always listen to Carnatic music at home. But my love of

00:08:57.680 --> 00:09:03.280
[Guest]: Hindustani music came up in college. Then, of course, you know, at that point, you either

00:09:03.280 --> 00:09:07.600
[Guest]: go to Delhi school or you go to, you know, do an MBA at that point. Those are the kind

00:09:07.600 --> 00:09:13.080
[Guest]: of standard options. And I had always wanted to, I think, join, I think, the government.

00:09:13.080 --> 00:09:18.800
[Guest]: In fact, I think I wanted to join the Foreign Service then, I think. So I did my MBA. And

00:09:18.800 --> 00:09:22.720
[Guest]: in my second year, I wrote the civil service exam and I failed. I mean, I mean, I wasn't

00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:30.520
[Guest]: high enough to get either the IFS or the IAS. And then, of course, I guess it's a sign of

00:09:30.520 --> 00:09:37.800
[Guest]: the elite networks that we were part of that I got this scholarship. I'm not sure I deserved

00:09:37.800 --> 00:09:43.080
[Guest]: it entirely, but I got the scholarship to go to England. So after my MBA, I worked for

00:09:43.080 --> 00:09:47.240
[Guest]: a brief period, three months with the Tata. They had the Tata Administrative Service,

00:09:47.240 --> 00:09:51.800
[Guest]: which was like the private sector equivalent of the IAS. But then they gave me leave actually

00:09:51.800 --> 00:09:56.720
[Guest]: to go abroad. And I went to Oxford to do, in fact, I went to do an MPhil in management

00:09:56.720 --> 00:10:01.960
[Guest]: studies because that's what I'd done in MBA, but I quickly switched to economics. And I

00:10:01.960 --> 00:10:08.760
[Guest]: think I had, again, a fairly unremarkable MPhil in PhD. I was still kind of unsure of

00:10:08.760 --> 00:10:15.720
[Guest]: what I wanted to do, you know, not completely confident that, you know, I had actually acquired

00:10:15.720 --> 00:10:21.880
[Guest]: because, you see, an Oxford PhD, unlike an American PhD, you know, it was completely,

00:10:21.880 --> 00:10:26.360
[Guest]: you know, open ended, you kind of did what you wanted. And today, for example, I mean,

00:10:26.360 --> 00:10:31.280
[Guest]: it's a dirty secret, you know, almost all my academic papers are empirical papers, but

00:10:31.280 --> 00:10:37.360
[Guest]: I have not done one course in econometrics all my life, you know, even though I'm a PhD

00:10:37.360 --> 00:10:43.560
[Guest]: in economics. So, you know, you could do that in if you went to England in those days. So

00:10:43.560 --> 00:10:50.800
[Guest]: I felt and then when I finished my MPhil, I did get an academic job. And the truth is,

00:10:50.800 --> 00:10:57.800
[Guest]: I felt that mediocrity shows up so clearly in academics, and feeling that I was an imposter

00:10:57.800 --> 00:11:03.560
[Guest]: and mediocre, I kind of ran away from academics as it were. And then I went to work for international

00:11:03.560 --> 00:11:08.920
[Guest]: institutions. And then I my first job was at in the GATT actually, at the time that

00:11:08.920 --> 00:11:14.520
[Guest]: the Uruguay round was being negotiated. I still remember, I was at the GATT, I was,

00:11:14.520 --> 00:11:20.960
[Guest]: you know, a young, very young, lowly officer. And I was assigned to be part of the intellectual

00:11:20.960 --> 00:11:25.360
[Guest]: property negotiations trips, you know, I don't know how many of you remember, but the the

00:11:25.360 --> 00:11:30.560
[Guest]: Uruguay round, the most contentious issue for India and for many developing countries

00:11:30.560 --> 00:11:37.280
[Guest]: was patent protection, and intellectual property. And, you know, at that stage, so while working,

00:11:37.280 --> 00:11:43.920
[Guest]: I did some, you know, fairly, not very sophisticated empirical research, showing that, you know,

00:11:43.920 --> 00:11:49.340
[Guest]: this trips agreement would be harmful for countries like India. And I even kind of roughly

00:11:49.340 --> 00:11:57.120
[Guest]: crudely quantified that. And I guess my early kind of moment of epiphany then was, this

00:11:57.120 --> 00:12:01.920
[Guest]: was not even kind of probably wouldn't have even been published in any academic journal.

00:12:01.920 --> 00:12:07.320
[Guest]: But I do remember, you know, when and those negotiations, by the way, were, were really

00:12:07.320 --> 00:12:10.680
[Guest]: contentious. I mean, I don't know how many of you recall that it was almost touch and

00:12:10.680 --> 00:12:15.320
[Guest]: go India was almost considering not signing on to it, because, because of the intellectual

00:12:15.320 --> 00:12:19.800
[Guest]: property things, because, you know, pharmaceutical prices would go up, access to medicine would

00:12:19.800 --> 00:12:26.560
[Guest]: come down. So I remember, and I, you know, did this work. So I remember my moment of

00:12:26.560 --> 00:12:31.720
[Guest]: kind of, you know, kind of epiphany, but also kind of sense of wonder of, you know, what

00:12:31.720 --> 00:12:36.280
[Guest]: the life of a policy economist could be. You know, I was working there and one of the Indian

00:12:36.280 --> 00:12:42.680
[Guest]: officials one day, this was, I think, 90, maybe three or 94. I don't know when it was.

00:12:42.680 --> 00:12:46.840
[Guest]: He came and he was a senior person, senior civil servant in the Indian government, who

00:12:46.840 --> 00:12:51.280
[Guest]: used to work in the commerce ministry. He came and said, Arvind, I have to tell you,

00:12:51.280 --> 00:12:57.760
[Guest]: you know, last week or a month ago, Carla Hills, who was the US trade negotiator, very

00:12:57.760 --> 00:13:04.840
[Guest]: tough lady, she was called Carla Crowbar Hills, because she wanted to price open markets in

00:13:04.840 --> 00:13:10.360
[Guest]: developing countries. And so what had happened was, when I wrote this, I think Montague was

00:13:10.360 --> 00:13:16.160
[Guest]: the Commerce Secretary at that point. So this official had passed it on to Montague and

00:13:16.160 --> 00:13:21.680
[Guest]: apparently, and Chidambaram was the Commerce Minister, and he had passed it on to Chidambaram.

00:13:21.680 --> 00:13:26.800
[Guest]: So this person came to me and said, Carla Hills came and met Mr. Chidambaram to say

00:13:26.800 --> 00:13:31.760
[Guest]: that, why are you Indians fussing over this intellectual property negotiations? You know,

00:13:31.760 --> 00:13:35.760
[Guest]: it's going to be win-win for all of us, it's good for India, etc. And then she said, look,

00:13:35.760 --> 00:13:39.880
[Guest]: I have a bunch of 10 studies to show that this is the case. And apparently, I don't

00:13:39.880 --> 00:13:44.480
[Guest]: know, of course, it was later confirmed, apparently, Mr. Chidambaram, the minister said, well,

00:13:44.480 --> 00:13:48.480
[Guest]: Ambassador Hills, I have another study which shows exactly the opposite. And he presented

00:13:48.480 --> 00:13:54.400
[Guest]: her my paper. And so that was a kind of wow moment for me that, you know, one could do

00:13:54.400 --> 00:13:58.920
[Guest]: policy research and have it taken seriously by policymakers. So that was a kind of quite

00:13:58.920 --> 00:14:03.680
[Guest]: a heady moment of, you know, and I was very young then. And then after that, of course,

00:14:03.680 --> 00:14:11.680
[Guest]: I went to work for the IMF. And, you know, again, fairly unremarkable career. But then,

00:14:11.680 --> 00:14:19.280
[Guest]: I mean, basically, my, my kind of academic life took off in around 2000, I think, I was

00:14:19.280 --> 00:14:23.160
[Guest]: the, you know, for the IMF, I, you know, IMF, you go around, you know, to all the countries

00:14:23.160 --> 00:14:30.720
[Guest]: in the world, I was the mission leader to Mauritius. And it's just a such an interesting

00:14:30.720 --> 00:14:36.160
[Guest]: country, you know, for so many reasons, literature, history, you know, the Indian presence there.

00:14:36.160 --> 00:14:44.640
[Guest]: And when I was in in Mauritius, I actually saw a festival that you only see in Chennai,

00:14:44.640 --> 00:14:50.040
[Guest]: you know, very unusual festival in Chennai, which is related to the God Kartikeya. I saw

00:14:50.040 --> 00:14:54.960
[Guest]: that actually, I saw that in Mauritius, you know, so it's kind of really a, I mean, just

00:14:54.960 --> 00:15:00.400
[Guest]: to see how traditions kind of persist, you know, in distant places. So I was working

00:15:00.400 --> 00:15:05.840
[Guest]: on Mauritius, fascinating country, there's a great Naipaul piece on Mauritius, you know,

00:15:05.840 --> 00:15:10.240
[Guest]: of course, Joseph Conrad was in Mauritius, you know, of course, the Amitabh Ghosh trilogy

00:15:10.240 --> 00:15:16.360
[Guest]: begins in at least part of it is in Mauritius. So I wrote a paper on Mauritius, basically

00:15:16.360 --> 00:15:22.160
[Guest]: saying, how can you explain this, this miracle? And I sent it to, you know, Danny Roderick,

00:15:22.160 --> 00:15:28.520
[Guest]: who was then a friend and a co author. And, you know, within kind of an hour of receiving

00:15:28.520 --> 00:15:34.400
[Guest]: that he said, Arvind, I want this for my volume. And then, of course, then, then I became a

00:15:34.400 --> 00:15:39.240
[Guest]: for about 10 years, I think I was doing hardcore economics research, but never situated in

00:15:39.240 --> 00:15:44.420
[Guest]: academia, I was never, I was always, you know, then at the IMF. So Danny and I did a series

00:15:44.420 --> 00:15:49.440
[Guest]: of research papers, then Raghu and I did a series of research papers that I did on my

00:15:49.440 --> 00:15:54.920
[Guest]: own, a number of research papers, then I moved to this think tank in Washington, the Peterson

00:15:54.920 --> 00:15:58.560
[Guest]: Institute for International Economics and the Center for Global Development. Because,

00:15:58.560 --> 00:16:03.960
[Guest]: you know, my, my academic research is mostly on, you know, development and global and,

00:16:03.960 --> 00:16:08.880
[Guest]: you know, the global economic system, and almost all of that. So I left the IMF partly

00:16:08.880 --> 00:16:14.760
[Guest]: also, because, you know, people think that, in government, you have to be restrained in

00:16:14.760 --> 00:16:18.720
[Guest]: your public utterances. And that was getting becoming true of the IMF as well, because

00:16:18.720 --> 00:16:25.080
[Guest]: actually, Raghu and I wrote a series of papers on aid, then I wrote some pieces on Nigeria,

00:16:25.080 --> 00:16:30.280
[Guest]: which I think senior management, they were having difficulty allowing it to be published.

00:16:30.280 --> 00:16:34.680
[Guest]: So I left because I wanted to write publicly much more. And then, of course, I wrote a

00:16:34.680 --> 00:16:41.000
[Guest]: book on China when I was in the Peterson Institute, which about the rise of China and so on. So

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:46.840
[Guest]: I got a bit into China as well. And then of course, this, you know, what is probably the

00:16:46.840 --> 00:16:51.720
[Guest]: most exciting three years and nine months of my life was the, you know, being Chief

00:16:51.720 --> 00:16:57.320
[Guest]: Economic Advisor, it was really a completely transformational experience for me in many,

00:16:57.320 --> 00:17:01.960
[Guest]: many ways, you know, what you learn about politics, about politicians, about the policymaking

00:17:01.960 --> 00:17:07.800
[Guest]: process, what you learn about oneself, you know, how you build teams. And of course,

00:17:07.800 --> 00:17:14.880
[Guest]: the other thing is, you know, is how should one kind of behave as a public intellectual

00:17:14.880 --> 00:17:19.080
[Guest]: in government, you know, what are the dilemmas that you face the, you know, the moral dilemmas

00:17:19.080 --> 00:17:24.600
[Guest]: and things, you know, so many, so many unusual things happened when I was in government,

00:17:24.600 --> 00:17:29.480
[Guest]: and so many choices had to be made. So so so and then, of course, now, I finished that

00:17:29.480 --> 00:17:35.240
[Guest]: and left a year before my second contract was about to end. Because I felt that, you

00:17:35.240 --> 00:17:41.040
[Guest]: know, I had personal reasons, but also, I felt that my usefulness, effectiveness was

00:17:41.040 --> 00:17:46.840
[Guest]: kind of reaching their limits. And so I was working as at the Kennedy School was teaching

00:17:46.840 --> 00:17:52.200
[Guest]: here. And now, of course, as of July one, I've joined Ashoka University. And so look

00:17:52.200 --> 00:17:56.480
[Guest]: forward to, you know, probably the last phase of my career.

00:17:56.480 --> 00:18:01.840
[Amit Varma]: That's a fascinating life, you managed to summarize into so little space, I have a couple

00:18:01.840 --> 00:18:06.240
[Amit Varma]: of follow up questions. And for one, I want to go a little bit back, because you know,

00:18:06.240 --> 00:18:09.880
[Amit Varma]: as you were talking about your childhood and growing up and going across India, and I felt

00:18:09.880 --> 00:18:13.840
[Amit Varma]: a little nostalgic, because even though I am like 15 years younger than you, I'm in

00:18:13.840 --> 00:18:19.240
[Amit Varma]: my mid 40s. Now, it strikes me that I also did a significant part of my growing up. Before

00:18:19.240 --> 00:18:25.260
[Amit Varma]: liberalization, I was also a privileged child, my father was a civil servant. So I would

00:18:25.260 --> 00:18:30.080
[Amit Varma]: imagine that, you know, just thinking of all of the people growing up in similar circumstances,

00:18:30.080 --> 00:18:34.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, in those times, certain kinds of music, which you end up listening to the certain

00:18:34.040 --> 00:18:38.560
[Amit Varma]: kind of books, which you end up reading, you know, everything that you kind of mentioned

00:18:38.560 --> 00:18:43.720
[Amit Varma]: about the magazines, and just sort of thinking about myself, I've often thought that what

00:18:43.720 --> 00:18:50.000
[Amit Varma]: that upbringing did to me is that I grew into a sort of default view of the world that I

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:56.160
[Amit Varma]: had where you take the necessity of this of state paternalism for granted, that, you know,

00:18:56.160 --> 00:19:00.280
[Amit Varma]: you have a certain approach to everything. And then later on, as you go through the years,

00:19:00.280 --> 00:19:05.320
[Amit Varma]: the scales fall off your eyes now in and you see the world differently in subtle ways.

00:19:05.320 --> 00:19:10.280
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, this journey would be different for everybody. Now, it's interesting that,

00:19:10.280 --> 00:19:13.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, at a certain point, you've done your MBA, you've completed that, and then

00:19:13.200 --> 00:19:17.280
[Amit Varma]: you go abroad, and you spent, you know, most of your career abroad. So my first sort of

00:19:17.280 --> 00:19:22.920
[Amit Varma]: question is that, were there moments where you felt that you could take a step back?

00:19:22.920 --> 00:19:26.040
[Amit Varma]: And you know, there were some scales that fell off, and you could take a step back and

00:19:26.040 --> 00:19:31.160
[Amit Varma]: something which had seemed one way to you, you know, seem different, like, would you

00:19:31.160 --> 00:19:34.800
[Amit Varma]: say that there was a process like that? Or was there a period of time where you felt

00:19:34.800 --> 00:19:39.360
[Amit Varma]: that you began to look at the world differently? And, you know, if so, what was the change

00:19:39.360 --> 00:19:44.200
[Amit Varma]: like whether thinkers who influenced you and or books that you know, kind of changed or

00:19:44.200 --> 00:19:49.280
[Guest]: shaped the way you looked at the world? Yeah, I don't think it would be accurate to say

00:19:49.280 --> 00:19:53.640
[Guest]: that there was one, you know, point of, you know, one or two epiphanic moments, we'd say,

00:19:53.640 --> 00:19:58.880
[Guest]: Oh, my God, whatever. So it was very much, I think, a gradual process. And as you said,

00:19:58.880 --> 00:20:03.840
[Guest]: I think this whole, you know, the state is part of your state. And, you know, it's part

00:20:03.840 --> 00:20:09.680
[Guest]: of your DNA growing up. I think the first thing kind of the intellectual changes, you

00:20:09.680 --> 00:20:14.680
[Guest]: go out, and you see, wow, you know, all that the state has done wrong, you know, the liberties

00:20:14.680 --> 00:20:20.800
[Guest]: it's taken away the, you know, the whole license control Raj and, you know, you kind of we

00:20:20.800 --> 00:20:25.240
[Guest]: used to take, you know, 100 and 200% tariffs as kind of, you know, normal, right? And then

00:20:25.240 --> 00:20:30.280
[Guest]: you go abroad and say, what, you know, 3%, 5% tariffs, and you know, what's going on

00:20:30.280 --> 00:20:34.600
[Guest]: kind of thing. And of course, then you read, I read the old, you know, the wonderful Bhagwati

00:20:34.600 --> 00:20:41.240
[Guest]: Desai Srinivasan literature, you know, you learn about that. And so I think that process

00:20:41.240 --> 00:20:48.480
[Guest]: of seeing what we were doing wrong, I think it just hits you gradually over time. But

00:20:48.480 --> 00:20:55.780
[Guest]: then, of course, I think, in some ways, you know, the journey in some ways gets completed,

00:20:55.780 --> 00:21:04.240
[Guest]: because then you say, well, but yes, markets, yes, freedom, yes, liberalism. But, you know,

00:21:04.240 --> 00:21:10.080
[Guest]: what about all the things that this, you know, the acts of omission that the state has committed,

00:21:10.080 --> 00:21:13.840
[Guest]: you know, we know the sins of commission, then you come back and you say, well, what

00:21:13.840 --> 00:21:21.080
[Guest]: about the sins of and so I think the last 10-15 years have been, I think, a lot about

00:21:21.080 --> 00:21:26.940
[Guest]: understanding and, and reflecting on, you know, state and markets in India, you know,

00:21:26.940 --> 00:21:31.520
[Guest]: what I call the whole stigmatized capitalism, how that's come about in a way that's detrimental

00:21:31.520 --> 00:21:36.480
[Guest]: to both capital and states. And so I think that's been kind of the intellectual journey,

00:21:36.480 --> 00:21:41.800
[Guest]: to some extent. And I remember, I think, in terms of intellectual influences, you know,

00:21:41.800 --> 00:21:47.240
[Guest]: I was reading a lot. But in the academic literature, I think that, you know, I would almost say

00:21:47.240 --> 00:21:53.360
[Guest]: that I learned kind of macroeconomics reading Paul Krugman's writings, actually, I would

00:21:53.360 --> 00:21:58.720
[Guest]: actually read almost everything that he wrote early on here, some, you know, wonderful,

00:21:58.720 --> 00:22:04.040
[Guest]: and just I think, just how to write clearly as an economist, I think, that's been a big

00:22:04.040 --> 00:22:09.200
[Guest]: obsession of mine. It's not just, you know, obviously, the ideas matter a lot, but actually,

00:22:09.200 --> 00:22:14.080
[Guest]: how do you make it communicable? And then, you know, both for me, Danny Rodrik and Paul

00:22:14.080 --> 00:22:20.800
[Guest]: Krugman were, were really very influential, both in content, you know, Danny's early writings

00:22:20.800 --> 00:22:26.000
[Guest]: on political economy were, I think, very, very insightful for me. So also to think about,

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:31.160
[Guest]: you know, you know, not just state and markets, but the whole, you know, because remember,

00:22:31.160 --> 00:22:35.600
[Guest]: when we used to speak about, you know, market failure, but I think, you know, the whole

00:22:35.600 --> 00:22:40.640
[Guest]: question about what is state failure was a very important issue. And therefore, understanding

00:22:40.640 --> 00:22:45.680
[Guest]: political economy, you know, what all the things going on, ideology, interests, institutions,

00:22:45.680 --> 00:22:50.920
[Guest]: the rich interactions between them, I think that was something that I always read about

00:22:50.920 --> 00:22:56.280
[Guest]: and followed, kind of very, very closely. And, you know, my second question arising

00:22:56.280 --> 00:23:00.080
[Amit Varma]: from that is that, you know, when I read your work, when I read your writings, and your

00:23:00.080 --> 00:23:04.660
[Amit Varma]: speeches and so on, I, I sense this deep sense of conviction, like you've very often spoken

00:23:04.660 --> 00:23:09.800
[Amit Varma]: about how during your time, as the chief economic advisor, you would wake up every morning excited

00:23:09.800 --> 00:23:13.760
[Amit Varma]: about the day because, you know, every day was so exciting. And obviously, it's exciting

00:23:13.760 --> 00:23:18.800
[Amit Varma]: because you actually get a chance to sort of make a change in the world. And earlier,

00:23:18.800 --> 00:23:23.280
[Amit Varma]: when you were, you know, talking about your sort of career that, you know, you do an MBA,

00:23:23.280 --> 00:23:27.800
[Amit Varma]: the civil services doesn't happen. So you go to Oxford. And after that, you know, you

00:23:27.800 --> 00:23:32.840
[Amit Varma]: feel academics is not the place for you, and then so on and your entire career path. And

00:23:32.840 --> 00:23:37.520
[Amit Varma]: there, it seemed like, okay, you're sort of going along a career path. And, you know,

00:23:37.520 --> 00:23:42.440
[Amit Varma]: there's a little bit of serendipity to it. So at what point did you start feeling this

00:23:42.440 --> 00:23:46.760
[Amit Varma]: sense of conviction about your work that look, my work can make a difference to the world?

00:23:46.760 --> 00:23:51.000
[Amit Varma]: Like, was there a time where you looked at something and said, this is a problem, I want

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:56.040
[Amit Varma]: to solve this problem, my next study is going to be about this, you know, was that a mindset

00:23:56.040 --> 00:24:00.040
[Amit Varma]: that you kind of had from the start? Or did it sort of, you know, evolve over a period

00:24:00.040 --> 00:24:01.040
[Guest]: of time?

00:24:01.040 --> 00:24:08.500
[Guest]: Yeah, I think that, you know, to be honest, it was never. I think the sequence was always,

00:24:08.500 --> 00:24:13.360
[Guest]: you know, you find yourself somewhere. And then you say, wow, this thing kind of like

00:24:13.360 --> 00:24:18.520
[Guest]: when I was in the GATT, I was working on the intellectual property negotiations. And then,

00:24:18.520 --> 00:24:23.600
[Guest]: you know, I said, Oh, my God, there's such a big issue involved here, that I wanted to

00:24:23.600 --> 00:24:29.680
[Guest]: work on that. Similarly, when I was in Mauritius, you know, again, I said, Wow, what a fascinating

00:24:29.680 --> 00:24:34.800
[Guest]: development experience this is, and I wanted to write. So it's been, it's never been consciously

00:24:34.800 --> 00:24:40.000
[Guest]: kind of trying to find something so much as, you know, I find myself somewhere, whatever

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:45.800
[Guest]: for all kinds of, you know, historical persistence reasons. And then, you know, you say, so all

00:24:45.800 --> 00:24:51.160
[Guest]: the aid stuff that we did, because I was working in the IMF, you know, in the research department,

00:24:51.160 --> 00:24:54.440
[Guest]: and you know, debate was going, you know, there's a raging debate between, you know,

00:24:54.440 --> 00:24:58.480
[Guest]: Billy Stille, Jeff Sachs, and others. And then, you know, I said, you know, maybe one

00:24:58.480 --> 00:25:04.500
[Guest]: can contribute here. So it was much more that, you know, not so much consciously seeking

00:25:04.500 --> 00:25:09.680
[Guest]: as you know, just finding yourself in places. And of course, I mean, to be honest, I, the

00:25:09.680 --> 00:25:15.180
[Guest]: thing is that, you know, my kind of principle guiding my research is that, A, the question

00:25:15.180 --> 00:25:20.540
[Guest]: has to be, you know, very important in terms of policy, you know, I'm not going to do anything

00:25:20.540 --> 00:25:25.480
[Guest]: that doesn't have a policy impact. And that it has to, you know, the contribution has

00:25:25.480 --> 00:25:33.140
[Guest]: to be novel and new. So the combination of important in terms of policy, but if I must

00:25:33.140 --> 00:25:37.340
[Guest]: have something new to say, otherwise, you know, it's not worth it, why bother, you know,

00:25:37.340 --> 00:25:43.260
[Guest]: so many. So, so there is a kind of, you know, kind of a shock or a novelty element to, you

00:25:43.260 --> 00:25:47.420
[Guest]: know, the stuff that I do. And part of it, of course, is, you know, part of that is also

00:25:47.420 --> 00:25:52.580
[Guest]: a way of getting people's attention to important policy issues. Because I remember the, even

00:25:52.580 --> 00:25:56.820
[Guest]: the, you know, the early patent work that I did, you know, I kind of said, you know,

00:25:56.820 --> 00:26:01.540
[Guest]: the loss is like $1 billion, or whatever. So putting numbers onto policy questions,

00:26:01.540 --> 00:26:06.660
[Guest]: I think is also something that I really, you know, that kind of, you know, really turns

00:26:06.660 --> 00:26:12.020
[Guest]: me on and motivates me as well. So the combination of, you know, new, important and new facts

00:26:12.020 --> 00:26:19.180
[Guest]: to kind of evidence to bring to bear. And the difference, I guess, why I don't, maybe

00:26:19.180 --> 00:26:25.660
[Guest]: haven't chosen this hardcore academic career is because, I mean, I've been less kind of

00:26:25.660 --> 00:26:30.980
[Guest]: obsessed with this whole, you know, you must show causation in kind of rigorous ways. I

00:26:30.980 --> 00:26:35.820
[Guest]: mean, for me, the big facts are as important as anything else that should be done. And

00:26:35.820 --> 00:26:40.100
[Guest]: I think facts change the world. I mean, I can give you examples of that, not not my

00:26:40.100 --> 00:26:44.540
[Guest]: own research, but lots of other people, it's much more the big facts that I think that

00:26:44.540 --> 00:26:50.860
[Guest]: have a big impact on the world and policymaking, as much as any kind of sophisticated attempt

00:26:50.860 --> 00:26:55.860
[Guest]: at showing it, well, you know, this happens because of this, you know, that's important,

00:26:55.860 --> 00:26:57.940
[Amit Varma]: but I think its role is

00:26:57.940 --> 00:27:02.500
[Amit Varma]: I'd love a couple of examples of big facts that had that kind of impact.

00:27:02.500 --> 00:27:08.620
[Guest]: So I think that, you know, to give you one example, you know, Karthik was on your show

00:27:08.620 --> 00:27:15.540
[Guest]: a few weeks ago. You know, for me, certainly that the finding that the work on teacher

00:27:15.540 --> 00:27:20.680
[Guest]: absenteeism in India, I think kind of changed a little bit the way we thought about the

00:27:20.680 --> 00:27:25.300
[Guest]: education debate in India, that, you know, you focus on or, you know, whatever, you know,

00:27:25.300 --> 00:27:28.780
[Guest]: you need to pour money, or you need to do other things. But then suddenly, this fact

00:27:28.780 --> 00:27:33.060
[Guest]: comes and hits you and says, wow, you know, this is like, you know, we've completely forgotten

00:27:33.060 --> 00:27:36.980
[Guest]: about, you know, teachers not showing up, and you know, what that does. And I think

00:27:36.980 --> 00:27:42.260
[Guest]: that set in train, a whole different way of looking at it. And I think, you know, similarly,

00:27:42.260 --> 00:27:47.420
[Guest]: I think, you know, the patent stuff that I spoke about, I think, that, and, you know,

00:27:47.420 --> 00:27:50.660
[Guest]: for example, if you look around the world, the whole, you know, the work that Piketty

00:27:50.660 --> 00:27:55.740
[Guest]: and his co authors have done, you know, kind of documenting, you know, the rise in a particular

00:27:55.740 --> 00:28:01.180
[Guest]: kind of inequality, top inequality, you know, you may disagree with the policy conclusions

00:28:01.180 --> 00:28:05.980
[Guest]: that follow. But the fact is, the world is a very different place in terms of understanding

00:28:05.980 --> 00:28:11.100
[Guest]: the world, because of knowing those facts about the world. So I think that there are,

00:28:11.100 --> 00:28:16.060
[Guest]: you know, the other, you know, just to give a personal example, is that, you know, in

00:28:16.060 --> 00:28:24.100
[Guest]: the economic survey, we did some work on migration, based on data that nobody had ever used in

00:28:24.100 --> 00:28:28.700
[Guest]: India and data that, you know, we had the privilege of getting access to because I was

00:28:28.700 --> 00:28:33.900
[Guest]: in government, this was the the railway data that we had. And my team and I, we made some

00:28:33.900 --> 00:28:39.220
[Guest]: use of it. And the numbers that came out, you know, were pretty striking, much bigger

00:28:39.220 --> 00:28:44.460
[Guest]: than what we had believed migration within India was all about. And of course, we presented

00:28:44.460 --> 00:28:50.340
[Guest]: it, I think it didn't gain a lot of traction, or people weren't quite didn't cotton on to

00:28:50.340 --> 00:28:55.660
[Guest]: it. But when the actual COVID crisis happened, the migrant crisis happened, it kind of showed

00:28:55.660 --> 00:29:01.740
[Guest]: that that work was, in some ways, you know, not incorrect in the quantification of the

00:29:01.740 --> 00:29:06.260
[Guest]: magnitudes and so on. So I think, you know, kind of facts are really, you know, but doing

00:29:06.260 --> 00:29:12.660
[Guest]: it very carefully, rigorously, but on important issues. And that's what I think is really,

00:29:12.660 --> 00:29:17.740
[Guest]: for me, is very, very challenging and important. And so, you know, even in government, I think

00:29:17.740 --> 00:29:27.140
[Guest]: people underestimate, you know, the quality of a simple chart. Because I remember very

00:29:27.140 --> 00:29:33.740
[Guest]: early on, this was, you know, I joined late 2014, early 2015. And we were having these

00:29:33.740 --> 00:29:37.980
[Guest]: discussions within government on, you know, what to do, etc. And I think, you know, there's

00:29:37.980 --> 00:29:41.900
[Guest]: not a there's not rocket science, I showed Mr. Arun Jaitley a chart of, you know, real

00:29:41.900 --> 00:29:47.940
[Guest]: wages declining, rural real wages declining. And, you know, I could see that, you know,

00:29:47.940 --> 00:29:52.900
[Guest]: he really made a real impression on him. He took note of it. And of course, he acted on

00:29:52.900 --> 00:29:57.380
[Guest]: it in ways that I'm not sure, even I don't know fully, but he did act on it. And I think

00:29:57.380 --> 00:30:04.020
[Guest]: that so things like that, I think, are really quite, quite important.

00:30:04.020 --> 00:30:08.060
[Amit Varma]: In fact, in one of your interviews, you use the phrase the Dracula effect, which is, you

00:30:08.060 --> 00:30:12.460
[Amit Varma]: know, to shine sunlight on something. So that it kind of becomes obvious. And I was struck

00:30:12.460 --> 00:30:17.900
[Amit Varma]: by that. So I want to follow sort of a couple of simultaneous parts during the rest of our

00:30:17.900 --> 00:30:22.900
[Amit Varma]: conversation. One is that, through your readings through your books, through your writings,

00:30:22.900 --> 00:30:27.180
[Amit Varma]: rather than through your books, I've, you know, gained a lot of insights about India's

00:30:27.180 --> 00:30:32.180
[Amit Varma]: economy post independence. So I want to sort of discuss that journey, the journey that

00:30:32.180 --> 00:30:38.140
[Amit Varma]: the Indian economy has made from 47 to here, and sort of where we are today, and obviously

00:30:38.140 --> 00:30:42.180
[Amit Varma]: zoom in on the years that you were actually in government and all of that. And at the

00:30:42.180 --> 00:30:48.380
[Amit Varma]: same time, I'm fascinated by, you know, your experiences within that beast, we call the

00:30:48.380 --> 00:30:53.340
[Amit Varma]: Indian state, and you know, your efforts to sort of bring about reform within that. And

00:30:53.340 --> 00:30:58.340
[Amit Varma]: many of my listeners are not sort of trained economists that they'll kind of, you know,

00:30:58.340 --> 00:31:03.180
[Amit Varma]: be familiar with all of this already. And so what I'll say is that, you know, to begin

00:31:03.180 --> 00:31:10.380
[Amit Varma]: with, can you give me a sense of, you know, go back to the choices that we made post independence

00:31:10.380 --> 00:31:16.260
[Amit Varma]: and maybe for two or three decades since and what was so unique about this experiment,

00:31:16.260 --> 00:31:21.700
[Amit Varma]: like you've spoken about what you called a precocious development model, and you know,

00:31:21.700 --> 00:31:26.620
[Amit Varma]: the two significant ways in which this was so strikingly different and a unique experiment.

00:31:26.620 --> 00:31:28.860
[Guest]: So can you can you elaborate on that a bit?

00:31:28.860 --> 00:31:34.140
[Guest]: Yeah. Um, so, you know, maybe I will, you know, jump first forward and then backward

00:31:34.140 --> 00:31:42.460
[Guest]: in time. And I'll come back to your question. So I guess, my first real academic piece on

00:31:42.460 --> 00:31:46.980
[Guest]: the Indian economy, which was also a kind of which, as you know, triggered a massive

00:31:46.980 --> 00:31:53.560
[Guest]: debate in India, which was this paper that Danny and I wrote on, you know, how growth

00:31:53.560 --> 00:32:01.180
[Guest]: took off in the 1980s, especially in 1979, even though the reforms began only in 1991.

00:32:01.180 --> 00:32:05.820
[Guest]: So you know, it provoked a massive discussion, because people said, no, no, no, you know,

00:32:05.820 --> 00:32:09.380
[Guest]: you know, because there are two camps, right, the camp that says, you know, you get growth

00:32:09.380 --> 00:32:15.340
[Guest]: through reforms. And then even the fact that actually, some people had noted that, you

00:32:15.340 --> 00:32:19.940
[Guest]: know, India's actually the growth take off happens actually 79, 1980. But you know, before

00:32:19.940 --> 00:32:23.660
[Guest]: that, we had the Hindu rate of growth, you grow at about three, three and a half percent.

00:32:23.660 --> 00:32:29.340
[Guest]: And then suddenly, from 1979, 80, onwards, we grow at about 6%. And so just highlighting

00:32:29.340 --> 00:32:34.420
[Guest]: that fact, and then saying, we have to try and understand this, that if you, you know,

00:32:34.420 --> 00:32:39.180
[Guest]: if you accept this, then how did we get this sudden, because the real acceleration is not

00:32:39.180 --> 00:32:44.180
[Guest]: between, you know, the 80s and 90s. Because remember, the 90s growth is pretty much the

00:32:44.180 --> 00:32:49.820
[Guest]: same as the 80s growth. So how did that happen? And so that was, for me, a real, you know,

00:32:49.820 --> 00:32:57.700
[Guest]: eye opener. And that, you know, my partial explanation for what happened in the 1980s,

00:32:57.700 --> 00:33:03.100
[Guest]: kind of then allows me to now kind of step back and say, come back to your question,

00:33:03.100 --> 00:33:07.980
[Guest]: which is that, you know, if you look at the kind of broad development choices that we

00:33:07.980 --> 00:33:12.420
[Guest]: made, you know, and choices to some extent is within quotes, because, you know, some

00:33:12.420 --> 00:33:17.020
[Guest]: of it is just persistence in history and, and personality. So, you know, how much active

00:33:17.020 --> 00:33:21.060
[Guest]: agency there was in these choices, when we use the word choice, we connote agency, which

00:33:21.060 --> 00:33:26.020
[Guest]: may not, at least historically may not be completely accurate. But I think there were

00:33:26.020 --> 00:33:32.180
[Guest]: two or three, I would say the big development choices that we made, right? One is, you know,

00:33:32.180 --> 00:33:37.660
[Guest]: from day one, you're a democracy, and not so. So if you look at, you know, there's a

00:33:37.660 --> 00:33:41.860
[Guest]: recent paper that I wrote with Rohit Lamba, which kind of brings it out, even more clearly,

00:33:41.860 --> 00:33:46.100
[Guest]: it was first there in the economic survey. If you think about it, if you look at the

00:33:46.100 --> 00:33:51.340
[Guest]: successful models of economic development, there were the two big models, right? One

00:33:51.340 --> 00:33:59.420
[Guest]: is Western Europe, and the US, which is essentially what happens is that you economic development

00:33:59.420 --> 00:34:06.560
[Guest]: happens over, you know, 150 200 years, and political development, you know, happens alongside.

00:34:06.560 --> 00:34:13.100
[Guest]: So there's slow economic and co terminus, co evolving, slow political development, and

00:34:13.100 --> 00:34:18.940
[Guest]: that's happened over 250 years, successful, and so on. The other model is the East Asian

00:34:18.940 --> 00:34:26.020
[Guest]: model, which is, you know, post 19, World War Two, you have a sudden burst of economic

00:34:26.020 --> 00:34:30.460
[Guest]: growth, you know, just to give put some numbers, Western Europe grew at about, let's say, two

00:34:30.460 --> 00:34:36.620
[Guest]: and a half percent per capita over 200 years, East Asia, you know, Japan, the Tigers, China,

00:34:36.620 --> 00:34:43.140
[Guest]: and now Vietnam, they grow rapidly, Korea, of course, they grow rapidly, over 50, 50,

00:34:43.140 --> 00:34:48.980
[Guest]: 60 years, and kind of achieve almost the same level of, you know, income as advanced countries.

00:34:48.980 --> 00:34:55.700
[Guest]: But so there's more rapid economic development, right? But there's a sequencing, you know,

00:34:55.700 --> 00:34:59.500
[Guest]: economic development comes first, and then political development follows. So you have

00:34:59.500 --> 00:35:04.180
[Guest]: these two kind of broad models. And India defies that, you know, India's model, which

00:35:04.180 --> 00:35:10.220
[Guest]: says from day one, you have democracy. So both economic development happens after or

00:35:10.220 --> 00:35:15.100
[Guest]: at least the attempt is made to happen after political development. So, so that kind of

00:35:15.100 --> 00:35:23.100
[Guest]: a, and remember, again, important historical fact is that it's not that this has not happened

00:35:23.100 --> 00:35:28.020
[Guest]: at all. There are only four or five other countries in the world that began democracy

00:35:28.020 --> 00:35:32.580
[Guest]: and embarked on economic development. But these are very small countries, you know,

00:35:32.580 --> 00:35:39.260
[Guest]: Costa Rica, Botswana, the Caribbean countries, and so on. So there's no comparable, you know,

00:35:39.260 --> 00:35:45.060
[Guest]: a large, so this is really striking. So therefore, what does that mean for development? And something

00:35:45.060 --> 00:35:49.820
[Guest]: that I'll come to in just a second. So that was one big choice, you know, democracy first,

00:35:49.820 --> 00:35:54.860
[Guest]: and then you embark on development. Then, of course, we had, you know, the whole commanding

00:35:54.860 --> 00:36:02.540
[Guest]: heights, etc, etc. But remember that the whole import substitution protecting domestic industry

00:36:02.540 --> 00:36:08.220
[Guest]: etc, etc, that India chose, whatever, we may have done it to a much more serious extent

00:36:08.220 --> 00:36:14.620
[Guest]: than say, Latin America did. But I think we should never forget that that choice of state

00:36:14.620 --> 00:36:20.460
[Guest]: led development was completely consistent with the zeitgeist of the times, you know,

00:36:20.460 --> 00:36:24.620
[Guest]: not just, you know, at that point, we thought, you know, the Russian model was doing very

00:36:24.620 --> 00:36:31.020
[Guest]: well. Remember, I think there's a very famous scene, event when Khrushchev goes to the United

00:36:31.020 --> 00:36:37.020
[Guest]: Nations, he picks up his shoe, and bangs it on the podium and says, we will bury you.

00:36:37.020 --> 00:36:41.580
[Guest]: And people thought he said, we're going to, you know, devastate a nuclear holocaust of

00:36:41.580 --> 00:36:47.100
[Guest]: the West. But actually, what he meant was, we economically, we will devastate you, we

00:36:47.100 --> 00:36:51.100
[Guest]: are model is doing so well, that we will, you know, show you that this is the right

00:36:51.100 --> 00:36:55.700
[Guest]: model. So if you look at Russia, if you look at the Great Depression, if you look at many

00:36:55.700 --> 00:36:59.700
[Guest]: developing countries, and of course, the whole rise of the welfare state in Europe as well.

00:36:59.700 --> 00:37:04.420
[Guest]: So, so that choice, I think, was not at all unusual, you may, you know, say, right, wrong,

00:37:04.420 --> 00:37:10.300
[Guest]: we can come to that later. But it was not, I think, what was really distinctive about

00:37:10.300 --> 00:37:19.820
[Guest]: India is that we combine that with this horrendously complicated system, which, you know, Rajaji

00:37:19.820 --> 00:37:25.460
[Guest]: famously called the License Quota Parmitraj, which, you know, there was the complexity,

00:37:25.460 --> 00:37:28.300
[Guest]: there was the corruption that happened, you know, which is going to be, you know, which

00:37:28.300 --> 00:37:34.780
[Guest]: is probably the most devastating legacy of all of that. But what was distinctive about

00:37:34.780 --> 00:37:40.600
[Guest]: that was, look, and this is something that people don't, you know, grasp sufficiently.

00:37:40.600 --> 00:37:44.940
[Guest]: When you protect, you want to help the domestic entrepreneur, you know, whatever, you know,

00:37:44.940 --> 00:37:49.260
[Guest]: the Bombay, we remember the Bombay plan, basically self serving saying, you know, protect so

00:37:49.260 --> 00:37:56.300
[Guest]: that you know, we can do it. So that's understood. But the whole, especially licensing, it actually

00:37:56.300 --> 00:38:02.660
[Guest]: taxed domestic producers. So whereas protection gives you, you know, is a favor granted to

00:38:02.660 --> 00:38:08.140
[Guest]: domestic industry, license is a tax on domestic industry, because you say, you can't produce

00:38:08.140 --> 00:38:11.580
[Guest]: more than so much, you know, every time you want to do this, you have to come and ask

00:38:11.580 --> 00:38:19.180
[Guest]: someone. So that tax on domestic production in a sense. So it was a very unusual model,

00:38:19.180 --> 00:38:24.580
[Guest]: where there was both import substitution, but a tax on domestic, basically domestic

00:38:24.580 --> 00:38:29.740
[Guest]: entrepreneurial activity was taxed in a way that very few countries do. And so that was

00:38:29.740 --> 00:38:35.020
[Guest]: the second kind of the big distinctive thing. The third, of course, I think big choice was

00:38:35.020 --> 00:38:40.540
[Guest]: that. And the way I like to put it is to say that, you know, this is the country, it's

00:38:40.540 --> 00:38:46.900
[Guest]: a premature democracy, democracies redistribute, we know that there's on top of that, there's

00:38:46.900 --> 00:38:53.200
[Guest]: the overlay of this hideous hierarchy that we call caste, and so on. So how do you redress

00:38:53.200 --> 00:38:58.860
[Guest]: historical inequality, I think, broadly, there would have been two ways of doing it. One

00:38:58.860 --> 00:39:03.860
[Guest]: is the whole opportunity route, you give everyone education, etc. But I call this, you know,

00:39:03.860 --> 00:39:10.220
[Guest]: we of course, did not do that, I think it was our second original sin. But instead,

00:39:10.220 --> 00:39:15.540
[Guest]: what we did was we went in for these guarantees. So I call this in the opportunity versus guarantee

00:39:15.540 --> 00:39:19.620
[Guest]: thing, you know, we went in for guarantees, which is the whole, what we call reservation

00:39:19.620 --> 00:39:25.180
[Guest]: and so on. And we can talk about so these were kind of three big choices that we made.

00:39:25.180 --> 00:39:33.260
[Guest]: Now, I want to link that, why did I jumpstart with 1980, 1990, is because, in some ways,

00:39:33.260 --> 00:39:42.220
[Guest]: what happened in the 1980s, was that that tax that we imposed on domestic industry,

00:39:42.220 --> 00:39:47.660
[Guest]: was when we kind of said, let's relax these tax, because remember, we call those pro business,

00:39:47.660 --> 00:39:52.780
[Guest]: not pro competition reforms, because the competition only began in 1990. After the opening up,

00:39:52.780 --> 00:39:58.980
[Guest]: the 80s reform was very much, you know, helping incumbents helping domestic business by giving

00:39:58.980 --> 00:40:04.020
[Guest]: them better access to inputs, technology, you know, all of that. So in some ways, the

00:40:04.020 --> 00:40:12.700
[Guest]: 80s rectify or began to rectify the distinctive tax that we impose. And that's kind of partly

00:40:12.700 --> 00:40:18.100
[Guest]: our explanation for why kind of, so if I wanted to put it provocatively, I would say that

00:40:18.100 --> 00:40:23.860
[Guest]: the 80s were in fact, the first decade that we actually did import substitution, because

00:40:23.860 --> 00:40:28.660
[Guest]: you know, we continue to protect our domestic industry, but we remove the tax on them. And

00:40:28.660 --> 00:40:32.540
[Guest]: so that happened, of course, the rest is history, we had a crisis, etc, etc.

00:40:32.540 --> 00:40:36.940
[Amit Varma]: I was sort of struck by these sort of broad strands which are happening through Indian

00:40:36.940 --> 00:40:42.180
[Amit Varma]: history. And it's not only economic, but obviously, the thinking encompasses that one, as you

00:40:42.180 --> 00:40:47.380
[Amit Varma]: pointed out is the whole command and control mindset, which, as you said, was, you know,

00:40:47.380 --> 00:40:52.220
[Amit Varma]: it was the belief of the time, it was completely the rational way to go. In fact, it would

00:40:52.220 --> 00:40:57.180
[Amit Varma]: have been going against the grain to not go that way. So that's completely understandable.

00:40:57.180 --> 00:41:01.140
[Amit Varma]: The second thing that really happens in the political domain, but the thinking carries

00:41:01.140 --> 00:41:05.980
[Amit Varma]: through I think, to how you should run the economy is that we don't build a new state,

00:41:05.980 --> 00:41:10.860
[Amit Varma]: we take over the existing colonial apparatus. And that is essentially the state. And that,

00:41:10.860 --> 00:41:15.660
[Amit Varma]: of course, has, you know, is incredibly oppressive. In the words of Somnath Lahiri, it's like

00:41:15.660 --> 00:41:20.980
[Amit Varma]: a state designed to be a policeman. And that mindset somehow seems to carry through when

00:41:20.980 --> 00:41:27.140
[Amit Varma]: not only do we do the sort of welfarism and the redistribution that is inevitable, because

00:41:27.140 --> 00:41:31.180
[Amit Varma]: we are a democracy, even though you know, we've reached that stage much earlier than

00:41:31.180 --> 00:41:35.500
[Amit Varma]: other democracies, which became wealthy before they became began to redistribute, we don't

00:41:35.500 --> 00:41:40.300
[Amit Varma]: have that option. But that's kind of fine. But not only do we do that, we also constrain

00:41:40.300 --> 00:41:44.820
[Amit Varma]: private capital and distrust private capital, like Nehru once said to JRD Tata, do not talk

00:41:44.820 --> 00:41:49.940
[Amit Varma]: to me of profit. It is a dirty word, stock quote. And that mindset seems to kind of carry

00:41:49.940 --> 00:41:54.780
[Amit Varma]: through. And like you, I'm inclined to excuse, you know, Nehru for some of these errors,

00:41:54.780 --> 00:41:58.220
[Amit Varma]: because they were very much the fashion of the time, like you said, import substitution,

00:41:58.220 --> 00:42:02.180
[Amit Varma]: and whatever. And like, you've pointed out that, you know, the industrial policy regulation

00:42:02.180 --> 00:42:07.420
[Amit Varma]: was a huge issue there. And you've also spoken elsewhere of bank nationalization being one

00:42:07.420 --> 00:42:12.780
[Amit Varma]: of the original sins. In fact, there's a great quote of yours, which I found, you know, would

00:42:12.780 --> 00:42:16.700
[Amit Varma]: not come from other economists, but from someone who reads a lot of literature, which is where

00:42:16.700 --> 00:42:22.780
[Amit Varma]: you've pointed out quote, over time, original sins become lasting virtues, stop quote. And

00:42:22.780 --> 00:42:26.420
[Amit Varma]: that's something I'll come back to, because I think some of the original sins are not

00:42:26.420 --> 00:42:31.340
[Amit Varma]: these specific policies, but a way of thinking about the world, which, you know, one can

00:42:31.340 --> 00:42:37.460
[Amit Varma]: argue, remains to this current day. And those debates sort of over the, you know, the 1980s,

00:42:37.460 --> 00:42:42.460
[Amit Varma]: your 2004 paper with Danny Roderick, the debates with Srinivasan, Panagaria, and so on. It's

00:42:42.460 --> 00:42:48.140
[Amit Varma]: very fascinating. But what kind of strikes me is that even these sort of reforms where

00:42:48.140 --> 00:42:53.300
[Amit Varma]: first you have the pro business reforms of the 80s, and you remove some of these restrictions,

00:42:53.300 --> 00:42:58.140
[Amit Varma]: and then the limited liberalization of 91, which, you know, did not touch factor markets

00:42:58.140 --> 00:43:02.380
[Amit Varma]: and so much more could have been done. But despite them being so limited, they had such

00:43:02.380 --> 00:43:07.660
[Amit Varma]: a massive impact on the people, you know, they caused so much good that one can only,

00:43:07.660 --> 00:43:11.260
[Amit Varma]: you know, fantasize about what the counterfactual could have been.

00:43:11.260 --> 00:43:16.460
[Guest]: Yeah. So I think I mean, just to go back on a couple of points on the historical thing,

00:43:16.460 --> 00:43:23.300
[Guest]: right. You know, when I try and understand why we did industrial licensing, and you know,

00:43:23.300 --> 00:43:29.780
[Guest]: that whole apparatus of regulating and taxing domestic industry. And, you see, one has to

00:43:29.780 --> 00:43:36.020
[Guest]: try and understand that. And one of the ways I think one partial explanation is that, to

00:43:36.020 --> 00:43:44.460
[Guest]: me, that it was kind of like the Gandhian overlay on kind of policy, which is that,

00:43:44.460 --> 00:43:49.980
[Guest]: you know, remember, in those days, we had this mortal fear of big, you know, big business,

00:43:49.980 --> 00:43:54.340
[Guest]: you know, people becoming too big, and therefore, you know, what will happen to our democracy

00:43:54.340 --> 00:43:58.900
[Guest]: if you know, if you have these very powerful actors. So in a sense, the only way one of

00:43:58.900 --> 00:44:03.380
[Guest]: the ways I understand this whole industrial licensing was to say that, you know, we don't

00:44:03.380 --> 00:44:08.420
[Guest]: want even domestic capital, we don't want them to that's why we had, you know, MRTP.

00:44:08.420 --> 00:44:17.100
[Guest]: And you know, the sticks and carrots given to remaining small, and preventing small from

00:44:17.100 --> 00:44:24.660
[Guest]: becoming big. I think I see that as, you know, the other big idea underlying the early choices,

00:44:24.660 --> 00:44:30.620
[Guest]: you know. So, you know, so if you go deeper than just saying, why did we tax, you know,

00:44:30.620 --> 00:44:34.340
[Guest]: domestic capital, I think the deeper thing is that, you know, this, you know, kind of

00:44:34.340 --> 00:44:39.220
[Guest]: thing we had for small, but it was Kadi village industries, you know, reservation for the

00:44:39.220 --> 00:44:44.940
[Guest]: small scale sector, you know, you know, all these laws applying, coming into play when

00:44:44.940 --> 00:44:51.500
[Guest]: you be exceeding certain size, and the whole fiscal regulatory apparatus, if you look back,

00:44:51.500 --> 00:44:57.940
[Guest]: was really about, you know, you know, favouring the small and preventing the becoming big.

00:44:57.940 --> 00:45:03.540
[Guest]: And I would argue that, you know, that aspect actually has come to hurt us quite a lot over

00:45:03.540 --> 00:45:07.780
[Guest]: time, especially when we look more recently at how we've done on, you know, low skill

00:45:07.780 --> 00:45:13.060
[Guest]: manufacturing, which, you know, exports of low skill manufacturing, which require really

00:45:13.060 --> 00:45:18.380
[Guest]: size, and so on. So I think that's one thing, one historical fact, I think, which we should

00:45:18.380 --> 00:45:24.860
[Guest]: keep in mind. The other is this whole premature democracy thing, right? I think that, as you

00:45:24.860 --> 00:45:31.340
[Guest]: rightly said, that, you know, the famous finding is that, you know, by definition, democracy,

00:45:31.340 --> 00:45:35.780
[Guest]: you know, if you look at the work of Ace Mogloo and Robinson, they almost say that, you know,

00:45:35.780 --> 00:45:40.980
[Guest]: democracy, in a sense, was a pre commitment to redistribution, in a way that just a promise

00:45:40.980 --> 00:45:47.940
[Guest]: of redistribution could not guarantee. So democracies have to redistribute. And of course,

00:45:47.940 --> 00:45:53.940
[Guest]: in addition, remember, what is distinctive about India, is that you not just have the

00:45:53.940 --> 00:46:03.220
[Guest]: imperative of redistribution on one axis of class, you also have it on, obviously, caste,

00:46:03.220 --> 00:46:06.740
[Guest]: you know, we have so you have it on the base of region, that's why we had all these policies

00:46:06.740 --> 00:46:12.260
[Guest]: which says, you know, region should be whatever. So when you have this desire to redistribute,

00:46:12.260 --> 00:46:18.660
[Guest]: or this imperative to redistribute on along not just one line, but many lines, you know,

00:46:18.660 --> 00:46:23.940
[Guest]: you're going to have a problem. And the premature part comes in is that, you know,

00:46:23.940 --> 00:46:29.060
[Guest]: your capacity to do that is just completely incommensurate with that. And kind of this

00:46:29.060 --> 00:46:34.500
[Guest]: speaks to your point about, you know, you inherit a state that's basically a kind of,

00:46:34.500 --> 00:46:41.380
[Guest]: you know, police state performing all these functions. It neither has the capacity nor

00:46:41.380 --> 00:46:47.540
[Guest]: the remember, I think we should be harsh on our early things, that after all the state at that

00:46:47.540 --> 00:46:51.380
[Guest]: point should have said, you know, we can't do many things. But we should provide say health

00:46:51.380 --> 00:46:56.100
[Guest]: and education to everyone, like what China did, they didn't do that. And of course, you don't

00:46:56.100 --> 00:47:02.580
[Guest]: have the fiscal capacity, either to deliver on redistribution, or in kind of raising the resources

00:47:02.580 --> 00:47:10.980
[Guest]: required to this. So that is why what happens is that redistribution willy nilly takes the form

00:47:10.980 --> 00:47:17.700
[Guest]: of messing with the price system. Because remember, prices are the, you know, if you can't,

00:47:17.700 --> 00:47:22.500
[Guest]: you know, today, we say, you know, redistribute, either you build schools or whatever education,

00:47:22.500 --> 00:47:28.020
[Guest]: or you have transfers, efficient transfers, whatever, right? But then you had neither.

00:47:28.020 --> 00:47:33.380
[Guest]: And then so the only way you redistribute is through messing around with the price system

00:47:33.380 --> 00:47:38.900
[Guest]: and distorting everything, you know, low prices for goods, cheap inputs. And so you just

00:47:38.900 --> 00:47:45.380
[Guest]: tamper systematically with the price system. And then that's what, you know, persists over time,

00:47:45.380 --> 00:47:51.620
[Guest]: it exacts a huge cost toll in terms of the economy. But again, I think you can be very

00:47:51.620 --> 00:47:57.540
[Guest]: critical about it. But I think the criticism should be more that conditional or not,

00:47:58.100 --> 00:48:04.180
[Guest]: either being able to, or choosing to do other forms of redistribution, then you're willy nilly

00:48:04.180 --> 00:48:11.060
[Guest]: left with this. So just to give you a modern day counterpart of this, you know, and this is the

00:48:11.060 --> 00:48:16.260
[Guest]: GST, and because I was kind of privy to these discussions. So take the GST discussion, for

00:48:16.260 --> 00:48:21.140
[Guest]: example, right, on the what should be the rate structure for the GST. And I think this really

00:48:21.140 --> 00:48:28.580
[Guest]: really typifies the early dilemma in some ways, except that it's 75 years on. So we all know that,

00:48:28.580 --> 00:48:33.700
[Guest]: you know, one rate is the best system, you know, by definition, you know, that's, it's clean,

00:48:33.700 --> 00:48:38.660
[Guest]: it's simple, it reduces corruption, it's easy to administer, it's going to improve your tax

00:48:38.660 --> 00:48:46.180
[Guest]: collection efficiency. And as the IMF shows, I think, after 2000, almost 80% of the countries

00:48:46.180 --> 00:48:52.580
[Guest]: that adopted the value added tax, which is the GST, went in for one rate. So in India,

00:48:52.580 --> 00:48:57.380
[Guest]: so we have this discussion, as you know, I wrote a report then saying, we should have three rates,

00:48:57.380 --> 00:49:04.020
[Guest]: not one rate. Now, think of it this way, that I would have been completely in favor of one rate,

00:49:04.660 --> 00:49:12.900
[Guest]: right. But remember, though, if you go for one rate, you will have to have some rates going up,

00:49:12.900 --> 00:49:17.380
[Guest]: right, you know, the rates for essential goods will have to have one rate by definition,

00:49:17.380 --> 00:49:21.140
[Guest]: some will go up, some will come down, but some will go up. And those going up will be

00:49:21.860 --> 00:49:26.340
[Guest]: affecting those, you know, those are goods generally consumed by poorer people. So what do

00:49:26.340 --> 00:49:33.300
[Guest]: you do? If you have instruments to protect, you know, those in some ways, you know, transfers,

00:49:33.860 --> 00:49:40.020
[Guest]: whatever, then of course, you would say, you know, one rate. But if you don't have those,

00:49:40.020 --> 00:49:44.340
[Guest]: you have a dilemma, right? Can you just say one rate and say, you know, go to hell? I mean,

00:49:44.340 --> 00:49:49.300
[Guest]: I think the political process will not allow that. What we've done historically, of course,

00:49:49.300 --> 00:49:55.140
[Guest]: is, you know, for every good we say, oh, this is consumed by this strata, this is consumed by this

00:49:55.140 --> 00:50:00.340
[Guest]: strata. So you have a multiplicity of rates. Each of them is, you know, trying to meet two

00:50:00.340 --> 00:50:05.220
[Guest]: objectives, the efficiency objective, and the kind of equity objective, but, you know, in all its

00:50:05.220 --> 00:50:11.060
[Guest]: messy complexity. So what I thought the compromise was that we can't do one, because state capacity

00:50:11.060 --> 00:50:18.420
[Guest]: is limited to do the compensation. Therefore, a compromise would be to have, you know, one rate,

00:50:18.420 --> 00:50:23.780
[Guest]: but applying to all goods at the lower end, you know, a standard rate, and of course, one demerit

00:50:23.780 --> 00:50:28.900
[Guest]: good, which, you know, applies to all the luxuries and so on. So in some ways, the three rate

00:50:28.900 --> 00:50:33.700
[Guest]: structure that, you know, that I propose, of course, in practice, and now it's become a multiple,

00:50:33.700 --> 00:50:38.660
[Guest]: multiple rate structure. And so it's gotten, it's really, it's gone back to the side of

00:50:38.660 --> 00:50:46.180
[Guest]: erring on complexity. And actually, so conceptually, therefore, you know, a three rate was kind of a

00:50:46.180 --> 00:50:52.420
[Guest]: compromise between efficiency and equity, because you couldn't ignore equity completely. But

00:50:52.420 --> 00:50:57.220
[Guest]: historically, what we did was, you know, we would have as many rates as there are categories of

00:50:57.220 --> 00:51:01.860
[Guest]: people we wanted to satisfy. And so that, in a sense, was the early dilemma that, you know,

00:51:01.860 --> 00:51:08.500
[Guest]: you didn't have, remember, in 2016, we at least have some mechanisms for redistribution, like

00:51:08.500 --> 00:51:14.340
[Guest]: PDS, Monrega, you know, now more and more cash transfers, but at that stage, we had nothing. So

00:51:14.340 --> 00:51:19.060
[Guest]: willy nilly, the price system had to bear the brunt of that. And that's where we were. So in

00:51:19.060 --> 00:51:24.180
[Guest]: some ways, therefore, you know, again, one has to be careful, it's not that, I mean, obviously,

00:51:24.180 --> 00:51:29.780
[Guest]: you know, maintaining and sustaining a democracy are fantastic achievements. And you know, what's

00:51:29.780 --> 00:51:37.540
[Guest]: happening to that now, of course, is not within my range of expertise. But to not realise that that

00:51:37.540 --> 00:51:44.660
[Guest]: created also some serious consequences and adverse consequences and burdens, one could almost call

00:51:44.660 --> 00:51:49.620
[Guest]: it the democracy tax, as it were the premature democracy tax, as it were, you know, you could

00:51:49.620 --> 00:51:53.620
[Guest]: see that happening. And to some extent, I think we're paying the price for that.

00:51:53.620 --> 00:51:58.260
[Amit Varma]: While you were speaking, a couple of related questions popped up to mind about sort of that

00:51:58.260 --> 00:52:02.420
[Amit Varma]: sort of that historic period before we come closer to present time. So I wonder what you

00:52:02.420 --> 00:52:08.020
[Amit Varma]: sort of think about these. One, it's always it's not always one in the last couple of years or

00:52:08.020 --> 00:52:12.740
[Amit Varma]: more, I've been reading up on it. And I've done a bunch of episodes on the history of and politics

00:52:12.740 --> 00:52:17.620
[Amit Varma]: of that period. It struck me that much as we think of the 50s as a time which were Nehruvian,

00:52:17.620 --> 00:52:23.300
[Amit Varma]: it strikes me that only Nehru was Nehruvian. And it was kind of serendipitous that he was a man in

00:52:23.300 --> 00:52:28.900
[Amit Varma]: charge. Now, it certainly seems to me to be this way, at least in the social domain. For example,

00:52:28.900 --> 00:52:34.020
[Amit Varma]: if you look at all the other tall leaders of the Congress from Patel to Prasad to Pant to

00:52:34.020 --> 00:52:40.180
[Amit Varma]: Lal Bahadur Shastri later, and all of those guys were leaders with a tilt towards Hindu nationalism,

00:52:40.180 --> 00:52:44.740
[Amit Varma]: like you know, Pant was CM of UP and Lal Bahadur Shastri was Home Minister when the idol was

00:52:44.740 --> 00:52:50.260
[Amit Varma]: installed in the Babri Masjid. So there it seems that Nehru was a man who kind of stood alone.

00:52:50.260 --> 00:52:55.380
[Amit Varma]: But in economics, is it necessarily the case that, you know, had Nehru not been there,

00:52:55.380 --> 00:52:58.740
[Amit Varma]: for example, I think socially, India would have looked very different. But economically,

00:52:58.740 --> 00:53:03.060
[Amit Varma]: would it have been any different? I mean, one hears of the exceptions like Rajaji and Masani

00:53:03.060 --> 00:53:08.820
[Amit Varma]: and so on, who were sort of, of a different bent of mind. But one, do your readings give you a

00:53:08.820 --> 00:53:13.060
[Amit Varma]: sense that there were different directions that could have happened? And it was this one individual

00:53:13.060 --> 00:53:17.780
[Amit Varma]: who happened to be there. And, you know, that's just how the luck played out. And the other

00:53:17.780 --> 00:53:22.660
[Amit Varma]: question which is related, so I'll, you know, ask it at the same time is that it seems to me that a

00:53:22.660 --> 00:53:30.340
[Amit Varma]: lot of the economic policy of, you know, that period was determined after actual intellectual

00:53:30.340 --> 00:53:35.300
[Amit Varma]: query where people were grappling with these questions in good faith. Even if we can look back

00:53:35.300 --> 00:53:39.700
[Amit Varma]: in hindsight and say this was a bad decision, or this was a good decision, they were grappling with

00:53:39.700 --> 00:53:45.460
[Amit Varma]: it in good faith and trying to figure it out on the basis of ideas. But what seems to me to have

00:53:45.460 --> 00:53:50.820
[Amit Varma]: happened towards the end of the 1960s, is that, you know, we know that a lot of Indira Gandhi's

00:53:50.820 --> 00:53:55.780
[Amit Varma]: leftward tail, the bank nationalization sphera, and so on and so forth, a lot of that leftward

00:53:55.780 --> 00:54:01.460
[Amit Varma]: tilt was because she had to politically position herself as being distinctive from the syndicate,

00:54:01.460 --> 00:54:07.380
[Amit Varma]: who were her rivals in the Congress. And it seems that at that point, there are sort of three other

00:54:07.380 --> 00:54:13.540
[Amit Varma]: imperatives that gradually come into the play and consolidate. One is political imperatives and the

00:54:13.540 --> 00:54:19.940
[Amit Varma]: incentives that politicians face, either if they are appealing to populism or to short termism,

00:54:19.940 --> 00:54:25.140
[Amit Varma]: because, hey, everybody's got their eye on the next elections. Second, the natural inertia that

00:54:25.140 --> 00:54:30.820
[Amit Varma]: sets in into any system, particularly a large bureaucratic system, like ours, and not just

00:54:30.820 --> 00:54:36.740
[Amit Varma]: inertia of action, but inertia of thought. And third, the interest groups which then get settled

00:54:36.740 --> 00:54:43.300
[Amit Varma]: in and entrenched and make it difficult to change anything. So was that perhaps a tragic shift,

00:54:43.300 --> 00:54:48.420
[Amit Varma]: which people don't remark on that we begin with policies that we can criticize today in hindsight,

00:54:48.420 --> 00:54:53.300
[Amit Varma]: but that were made in good faith with people like Nehru actually engaging with ideas, but we move

00:54:53.300 --> 00:54:58.500
[Amit Varma]: to a cynical time where ideas don't really matter. And you have these incentives from these three

00:54:58.500 --> 00:55:05.940
[Guest]: different directions, driving policy. Yeah, I mean, really a terrific question. You see,

00:55:05.940 --> 00:55:12.420
[Guest]: I think that we forget when we look at kind of histories of nations, and that there are these

00:55:12.420 --> 00:55:19.940
[Guest]: critical junctures in countries' history when, you know, some special things can happen. You know,

00:55:19.940 --> 00:55:24.740
[Guest]: it could be at the time of independence, it could be a revolution, it could be a crisis.

00:55:24.740 --> 00:55:29.220
[Guest]: So there is something I feel if you look at historically, something distinctive about

00:55:29.220 --> 00:55:34.500
[Guest]: certain points in time. And I think, you know, clearly for India, that distinctive period was

00:55:34.500 --> 00:55:40.580
[Guest]: the post-independence period, partly a result of this. So I think therefore, kind of two or

00:55:40.580 --> 00:55:47.380
[Guest]: three things come together, right? One is this moment of, you know, idealism, and so on. And

00:55:47.380 --> 00:55:53.620
[Guest]: that's critical juncture. Second is almost intrinsic to these movements is you are going to

00:55:53.620 --> 00:56:01.700
[Guest]: have politicians with the temperament of, you know, let's set aside personal things, and whatever.

00:56:01.700 --> 00:56:07.460
[Guest]: Maybe the third aspect what happened in those early years also was kind of the dominance of

00:56:07.460 --> 00:56:12.420
[Guest]: the Congress Party. So you don't have, you know, political competition. I'm not saying that's

00:56:12.420 --> 00:56:16.820
[Guest]: necessarily good. But you did have this kind of, you know, because when Mrs. Gandhi comes into

00:56:16.820 --> 00:56:20.660
[Guest]: power, it becomes more competitive. And as Atul Kohli and others have shown, you know, that,

00:56:20.660 --> 00:56:24.740
[Guest]: you know, that creates the whole dynamic that you mentioned about interests, and you know,

00:56:24.740 --> 00:56:30.500
[Guest]: you need money and so on. So I think a combination of these three things, you know, the critical

00:56:30.500 --> 00:56:36.180
[Guest]: moment, the idealism, the quality of leaders, you know, the monopoly of the political monopoly,

00:56:36.180 --> 00:56:41.620
[Guest]: which kind of allows you to do certain things that might otherwise not happen. But then that

00:56:41.620 --> 00:56:47.540
[Guest]: comes to the other point that you raised about, you know, was it all Nehru? You know, I think it's

00:56:47.540 --> 00:56:52.420
[Guest]: undeniable that, you know, state led industrialization, you know, the emphasis on

00:56:52.420 --> 00:56:56.820
[Guest]: technology, the emphasis on higher education, I think that certainly comes from, you know,

00:56:56.820 --> 00:57:00.180
[Guest]: you read Discovery of India and things, you know, what he wants the, you know, the whole

00:57:00.180 --> 00:57:04.980
[Guest]: rationalism emphasis on science, because as you know, I think somewhere in Discovery of India,

00:57:04.980 --> 00:57:10.900
[Guest]: he says, quite prescient, I mean, quite accurately, that if you look at history, for example,

00:57:10.900 --> 00:57:20.260
[Guest]: around 1450, Mughal India, Aztec America, Aztec Mexico, the Ottoman Empire, were, you know, and

00:57:20.260 --> 00:57:25.460
[Guest]: of course, Ming China, were at the top of, you know, development. And that's when the Great

00:57:25.460 --> 00:57:30.260
[Guest]: Reversal happens, you know, from about 1500 1600 onwards, and then you have the Great Reversal,

00:57:30.260 --> 00:57:35.700
[Guest]: where the two rich countries become poor. And Nehru's point is that even then, we were losing

00:57:35.700 --> 00:57:40.900
[Guest]: this edge in science and technology, which kind of contributed. So he was very much into that,

00:57:40.900 --> 00:57:50.420
[Guest]: and therefore, but having said that, you know, he had a really dominant role, I think we forget that,

00:57:50.420 --> 00:57:55.940
[Guest]: you know, one agriculture, you know, agricultural income was never allowed to be taxed, not because

00:57:55.940 --> 00:58:01.060
[Guest]: of Nehru, he would have happily taxed it, it's because of, you know, Sardar Patel and the whole,

00:58:01.060 --> 00:58:06.980
[Guest]: you know, agricultural thing. Then you also have, as I just said, you know, the overlay of, you

00:58:06.980 --> 00:58:12.500
[Guest]: know, small, remaining small, it's not just a Nehruvian obsession, I think it's also this, you

00:58:12.500 --> 00:58:17.300
[Guest]: know, broader obsession with remaining small, which is, I think, you know, partly a Gandhi

00:58:17.300 --> 00:58:23.860
[Guest]: legacy, you know, village and small and so on. And of course, also, we forget that, you know,

00:58:23.860 --> 00:58:29.540
[Guest]: I think Nehru's instincts would have been to push land reform much more. But you know, land reform

00:58:29.540 --> 00:58:33.780
[Guest]: never went anywhere, because partly it was his own democratic instinct, you know, you don't want

00:58:33.780 --> 00:58:39.140
[Guest]: anything by coercion, but partly there was this broader thing, I think. So therefore, while his

00:58:39.140 --> 00:58:46.260
[Guest]: imprint was very strong, you know, he loved these big temples and dams and things, you know,

00:58:46.260 --> 00:58:50.020
[Guest]: so all of that, that whole commanding heights, I think is very much him, but there were lots of

00:58:50.020 --> 00:58:56.740
[Guest]: other things, which perhaps were not due to him. And, you know, again, counterfactual history is

00:58:56.740 --> 00:59:01.700
[Guest]: very difficult, because my sense is that, and I think it's an important point that we forget,

00:59:02.420 --> 00:59:11.220
[Guest]: that I'm not sure, you know, the whole Rajaji's strand of thinking, whether that was ever dominant

00:59:11.220 --> 00:59:17.460
[Guest]: enough to have, you know, because at that stage, you know, people were completely unfamiliar with

00:59:17.460 --> 00:59:23.220
[Guest]: how a market economy in all its kind of full blown thing functions. So I think it would have been,

00:59:23.220 --> 00:59:28.020
[Guest]: you know, I think our choices, even looking back, I think our choices would have been,

00:59:28.020 --> 00:59:33.220
[Guest]: you know, statism or less statism, never, you know, a full blown kind of market economy. But

00:59:33.220 --> 00:59:36.980
[Guest]: I think some of the more egregious, I mean, industrial licensing, I think, was something

00:59:36.980 --> 00:59:42.820
[Guest]: that we could have really avoided. And of course, I think, you know, I'm just being, you know,

00:59:42.820 --> 00:59:49.300
[Guest]: unnecessarily kind of, you know, bold here. But I think, had we done the education and health

00:59:49.300 --> 00:59:55.060
[Guest]: that a state should have done, and, you know, not had industrial licensing, for example,

00:59:55.060 --> 00:59:59.620
[Guest]: and allowed actually domestic entrepreneurship to flourish, you know, maybe, you know,

00:59:59.620 --> 01:00:04.020
[Amit Varma]: trajectory of Indian history would have been different. On that wistful note, let's take a

